title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p><fr:strong>Claim 1:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is closed. Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X\setminus  K]]></fr:tex>. Then for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in  K]]></fr:tex>, let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[r_{z}>0]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[s_{z}>0]]></fr:tex> be such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[B_{r_{z}}(z)\cap  B_{s_{z}}(x)=\emptyset .]]></fr:tex>
We can do this for every <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in  K]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{B_{r_{z}}(z)\}]]></fr:tex> forms an <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-001S.xml"
addr="ca-001S"
title="Cover of a subset of a metric space">open cover</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link
type="external"
href="001T">compact</fr:link>, it has a finite subcover: <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B_{r_{1}}(z_{1})]]></fr:tex>, …, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B_{r_{k}}(z_{k})]]></fr:tex> which covers <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>. Let
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[s=\min (s_{z_{j}}\mid  j=1,…,k)\}]]></fr:tex>
Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B_{s}(x)\cap  B_{z_{j}}(z_{j})=\emptyset ]]></fr:tex> for each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[j=1,…,k]]></fr:tex>. Then
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[B_{s}(x)\cap (B_{r_{1}}(z_{1})\cup …\cup  B_{r_{k}}(z_{k}))=\emptyset ,]]></fr:tex>
so we must have
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[B_{s}(x)\subseteq  X\setminus  K.]]></fr:tex>
Then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X\setminus  K]]></fr:tex> is open iff <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is closed (by <fr:link
type="local"
href="ca-0014.xml"
addr="ca-0014"
title="A set is open iff its complement is closed">A set is open iff its complement is closed</fr:link>).</fr:p>

<fr:p><fr:strong>Claim 2:</fr:strong> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is bounded. For any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{0}\in  K]]></fr:tex>, pick <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{B_{n}(x_{0})\mid  n\in \mathbb {N}\}]]></fr:tex> as an open cover of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex>. Then there exists a finite subcover. Since <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B_{m}(x_{0})\subseteq  B_{n}(x_{0})]]></fr:tex> for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m\leq  n]]></fr:tex>, this means there exists an <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[N\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K\subseteq  B_{N}(x_{0})]]></fr:tex>. This implies <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[K]]></fr:tex> is bounded.</fr:p><html:span
